I. The Constraint‚ÄìPower Invariant

Doctrine Statement

Every capability granted within the Pantheon must explicitly declare its attached costs, binds, and constraint surfaces.

Rationale

All systems that grant power create lock-in vectors.
Explicitly modeling these vectors prevents hidden coercion, collapse, or corruption drift.

Implementation Rules
	‚Ä¢	Every daemon/module requires:
	‚Ä¢	Capability description
	‚Ä¢	Constraint ledger
	‚Ä¢	Exit conditions
	‚Ä¢	Reversal pathways

‚∏ª

II. The Two-Leg Entry Protocol

Doctrine Statement

No Pantheon operator or subsystem may commit across all dependency axes simultaneously.

Operational Meaning

Every deployment must preserve:
	1.	Functional engagement
	2.	Escape or renegotiation pathway

‚∏ª

Failure Condition

If a system requires:
	‚Ä¢	identity lock
	‚Ä¢	total resource lock
	‚Ä¢	irreversible narrative lock

‚Üí Deployment pauses pending audit.

‚∏ª

III. The 2/3 Slack Principle

Doctrine Statement

Pantheon outputs and architectures must intentionally preserve interpretive and operational slack.

Purpose

Slack enables:
	‚Ä¢	collaboration entry points
	‚Ä¢	mutation pressure
	‚Ä¢	resilience against overfitting
	‚Ä¢	multi-perspective integration

‚∏ª

Design Guidance

Pantheon artifacts should:
	‚Ä¢	solve ~2/3 of a conceptual space
	‚Ä¢	leave structured hooks for extension
	‚Ä¢	embed reflective silence zones

